ich involves `Class.forName(lambdaClsOwner)`. I’m wondering if our test creates a `nextName` with \"$$Lambda,\" since Java lambda names can look strange and may not be valid class names. Also, I need to consider whether the coverage filter includes certain internal packages, and how it interacts with the user-code-filter, which currently excludes tests. I'm curious about how that impacts metadata recording for dynamic access.\n[thinking] \n[thinking] **Examining coverage instrumentation**\n[thinking] \n[thinking] I’m considering whether the call site coverage relies on instrumentation rather than configuration. The dynamic access call site coverage report likely comes from an agent that records dynamic metadata, but only if the target is included. That’s an important detail! It seems essential that the \"user-code-filter\" only includes the library. I suspect that forging dynamic-access coverage may instrument library call sites independently, which could affect how data is reported. This needs further thought.\n[thinking] \n[assistant-event] thinking_end\n[assistant-event] text_start\n[assistant] Added a dedicated Scala test for the active dynamic-access class:\n[assistant] \n[assistant] - `tests/src/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor-typed_2.13/1.6.0/src/test/scala/org_apache_pekko/pekko_actor_typed_2_13/LoggerClassTest.scala`\n[assistant] \n[assistant] The test creates a lambda-backed typed `Behavior` via public Pekko APIs and accesses `context.log`, which drives `ActorContextImpl` through `LoggerClass.detectLoggerClassFromStack` and should reach the remaining `Class.forName` call site in `LoggerClass.scala`.\n[assistant] \n[assistant] I did not run tests, per workflow instructions.\n[assistant-event] text_end\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Examining untracked metadata**\\n\\nI’m thinking about an untracked metadata directory that seems to exist before. It’s crucial I d